06530nam a22012855i 9780691232454DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212017nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912324547 a10.1515/97806912324542doi  a(DE-B1597)585070  a(OCoLC)1257324247  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aNAT0120002bisacsh04a597.32231 aSpeedie, Colin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Sea Monster's Tale :bIn Search of the Basking Shark /cColin Speedie. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (288 p.) :bb/w line drawings, maps, and 8pp color insert  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWild Nature Press00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tThe Early History -- tThe First Hunters -- tChanging Views -- tAnthony Watkins, the Pioneer in Scotland -- tThe Post-War Hunt -- tThe Flag Drops -- tReality Bites -- tIn Action at Last -- tThe 1947 Season -- tThe Independent Operators -- tThe Hunt Beyond Scotland -- tWe Set Sail -- tThe Battle Begins -- tThe Early Surveys -- tSeeking Answers About a Sea Monster -- tSeeking Answers About a Sea Monster -- tThe End of the Line -- tWhere Do We Go from Here? -- tSources -- tAcknowledgements -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere are few marine creatures as spectacular as the Basking Shark. At up to 11 metres in length and seven tonnes in weight, this colossal, plankton-feeding fish is one of the largest in the world, second only to the whale shark. Historically, Basking Sharks were a familiar sight in the northern hemisphere - off the coasts of Norway, Scotland, Ireland, Canada and the USA, for example. In an 18th Century world without electricity, they became the focus of active hunting for their huge livers containing large amounts of valuable oil, primarily used in lamps.Catch numbers were small enough to leave populations largely intact, but during the 20th Century a new breed of hunter joined the fray, some driven as much by a need for adventure as for financial gain. With improved equipment and experience, they exploited the shark on an industrial scale that drastically reduced numbers, leading to localised near-extinction in some areas.From the 1970's onward a new generation took to the seas, this time with conservation in mind to identify where the shark might still be found in the waters around the British Isles, employing new technologies to solve long-standing mysteries about the behaviour of this elusive creature. Using the best of both old and new research techniques, the case was built to justify the species becoming one of the most protected sharks in the oceans.Today, the Basking Shark is a much-loved cornerstone of our natural heritage. There are positive signs that the population has stabilised and may even be slowly recovering from the damage of the past, proving that timely conservation measures can be effective. Join us on a journey amidst wild seas, places, people and conservation history in the battle to protect this iconic creature - a true sea monster's tale.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBasking sharkxConservation. 0aBasking sharkzBritish Isles. 0aBasking shark. 0aShark fishingxHistory. 7aNATURE / Animals / Fish.2bisacsh  aAchill Island.  aAghia Eireini.  aBarclay, John.  aBarmoy.  aBarrel Jellyfish.  aBerrow, Simon.  aBorn Free Foundation.  aCarradale Incident.  aChaplain, Lieutenant.  aCornaig Venture.  aCornwall Wildlife Trust.  aCorryvreckan.  aDawson, George Mercer.  aEagle.  aEvans, Peter.  aFarmery, Scott.  aForever Changes.  aFranleon II.  aGalway hooker.  aGannet.  aGyll-Murray, John